<kml>

<concept name=Break><system-documentation name=Break>
<superconcept name=Damage>

<definition>

  Break an object so that it can no longer perform its function.  

</definition>

<requiredslotlist>

  <slotdescription name=object>
     The object that's broken.
  </slotdescription>

</requiredslotlist>

<primaryslotlist>

  <slotdescription name=agent>
    the entity that caused the break to occur.
  </slotdescription>

  <slotdescription name=instrument>
    the thing that was used to break the object.
  </slotdescription>

  <slotdescription name=by-means-of>
    the event that caused the break to occur.
  </slotdescription>

</primaryslotlist>

<examplesentencelist>

  <examplesentence>
    <text>Bubba broke the TV with a bat.</text>
    <slotdescription name=object>the TV</slotdescription>
    <slotdescription name=agent>Bubba</slotdescription>
    <slotdescription name=instrument>a bat</slotdescription>
  </examplesentence>
  <comment>
     The TV ceases to perform its function.  If its broken 
     permanently, use <conceptref name=Ruin> to describe
     the action.
  </comment>

  <examplesentence>
    <text>The cup broke when it hit the floor. </text>
    <slotdescription name=object>the cup</slotdescription>
    <slotdescription name=by-means-of>hit the floor (a <conceptref name=Collide>)</slotdescription>
  </examplesentence>
  <comment>
     The cup ceases to perform its function of being a container.
  </comment>

  <examplesentence>
    <text>Fido broke his leash. </text>
    <slotdescription name=agent>Fido</slotdescription>
    <slotdescription name=object>Fido's leash</slotdescription>
  </examplesentence>
  <comment>
     Fido's leash ceases to perform its function of restraint.
     See also <conceptref name=Detach> for an encoding of the 
     consequences of this action.
  </comment>

</examplesentencelist>

<neighborlist>

  <neighbor name=Breach>
     A breach is a special kind of break in which a barrier is 
     punctured, creating a portal through it.
  </neighbor>
  
  <neighbor name=Destroy>
     A destroy is a special kind of break which causes an object 
     to cease to exist.
  </neighbor>

  <neighbor name=Ruin>
     A ruin is a special kind of break.  A ruin breaks an object 
     permanently so it can never again perform its function.
  </neighbor>

</neighborlist>

</kml>


